('carbon-credit-trading-india', 'problem',
 'Carbon Credit Trading India | Market Advisory & Strategy',
 'Expert advisory on carbon credit trading in India. Navigate CCTS compliance, voluntary carbon markets, and carbon pricing strategy with Bombay Breed.',
 'Carbon Credit Trading in India: Strategy & Advisory',
 'India''s carbon credit trading landscape is transforming with the Carbon Credit Trading Scheme (CCTS) creating a compliance market alongside the established voluntary carbon market. Bombay Breed helps corporates, project developers, and investors navigate this dual-market environment with strategic positioning and transaction advisory.',
 '{"introduction":"India is building one of the world''s largest compliance carbon markets through CCTS, while its voluntary carbon market already hosts significant CDM and VCS project portfolios. Understanding how to position across both markets is a strategic imperative for energy-intensive industries and project developers.","the_problem":"Most Indian corporates are unprepared for compliance carbon trading. They lack internal carbon pricing mechanisms, trading expertise, and the strategic communications capability to position carbon market participation as a value driver rather than a cost centre.","our_approach":"We provide end-to-end carbon market advisory: from compliance readiness assessment and carbon pricing strategy to transaction structuring guidance and investor-facing carbon market communications.","market_risks":"Key risks include: CCTS pricing volatility during initial trading phases, voluntary market integrity concerns affecting credit values, Article 6 corresponding adjustment requirements, and CBAM interaction effects on export-oriented industries."}',
 '[{"question":"When will carbon credit trading start in India?","answer":"India''s Carbon Credit Trading Scheme (CCTS) is being implemented in phases, with the compliance market framework established under the Energy Conservation Act amendments. Obligated entities in energy-intensive sectors will be the first participants."},{"question":"What is the difference between voluntary and compliance carbon markets in India?","answer":"The voluntary market allows companies to buy credits voluntarily for CSR or net-zero goals. The compliance market (CCTS) will mandate emission reductions from designated sectors, creating legally binding trading obligations with government-set targets."},{"question":"How should Indian companies prepare for carbon credit trading?","answer":"Start with internal carbon pricing, baseline emissions measurement, reduction pathway planning, and trading strategy development. Companies that build these capabilities early will have a significant advantage when compliance trading begins."}]',
 '[{"slug":"carbon-market-advisory-india","title":"Carbon Market Advisory","type":"capability"},{"slug":"ccts-compliance-india","title":"CCTS Compliance","type":"regulation"},{"slug":"article-6-advisory","title":"Article 6 Advisory","type":"capability"}]',
