('cbam-india-exporters-guide', 'problem',
 'CBAM India Exporters Guide | Steel, Cement & Aluminium',
 'Comprehensive CBAM guide for Indian exporters. Understand carbon border adjustment costs, reporting requirements, and compliance strategy for steel, cement, and aluminium.',
 'CBAM Guide for Indian Exporters',
 'The EU''s Carbon Border Adjustment Mechanism (CBAM) will impose carbon costs on Indian steel, cement, aluminium, fertiliser, and hydrogen exports to Europe. Bombay Breed helps Indian exporters understand their CBAM exposure, prepare compliance systems, and develop strategic responses.',
 '{"introduction":"CBAM is the EU''s mechanism to prevent carbon leakage by imposing a carbon cost on imports. For Indian exporters — particularly in steel, cement, and aluminium — this represents a significant new cost and compliance burden that requires strategic preparation.","the_problem":"Most Indian exporters are still in awareness mode on CBAM. The reporting requirements are complex, the cost implications are material, and the strategic options (invest in decarbonisation vs. absorb costs vs. redirect trade) require sophisticated analysis.","our_approach":"We provide CBAM readiness assessments, emissions calculation support, reporting system design, and strategic response planning. We also help exporters communicate their CBAM preparedness to investors and trade partners."}',
 '[{"question":"Which Indian products are affected by CBAM?","answer":"Steel, cement, aluminium, fertilisers, hydrogen, and electricity. India''s steel and aluminium sectors face the largest exposure given EU export volumes."},{"question":"When does CBAM become fully operational?","answer":"CBAM is in its transitional reporting phase now. Full implementation with financial obligations begins in 2026, with certificates required for embedded emissions in covered products."},{"question":"How much will CBAM cost Indian exporters?","answer":"Costs depend on the carbon intensity of production processes. Indian steel producers with higher carbon intensity than EU benchmarks face significant CBAM certificate costs per tonne of exports."}]',
